crm__abridgeimplementation__productfeedb.title: Product Feedback
crm__abridgeimplementation__productfeedb.value:
Based on the conversation, here is the product feedback provided:

• Positive endorsement of product value: Misty indicated that seasoned users are highly dependent on Abridge and expressed frustration when it wasn't working ("today wrecked the world. They're like, what do I do? I don't have Abridge"). She also mentioned that if hesitant providers would just try it, they would see it's a benefit, particularly for documenting clinical decision making.

• Comparison to competitor: Misty noted that their EMR software is developing its own AI documentation tool but described it as "clunky," comparing the choice between solutions to "Android and iPhone" - suggesting users need to find what suits them best. This indicates Abridge is viewed favorably compared to the native EMR solution.

• Adoption challenge: While not direct product feedback, Misty identified that getting non-users to adopt the tool remains a challenge, suggesting that initial trial/onboarding experience is critical for conversion.

crm__abridgeimplementation__questions__t.title: Questions
crm__abridgeimplementation__questions__t.value:
Questions Asked by Misty Hickman (Prospect) and Answers from Claire Fleming (Abridge)

Question 1: Can we turn on production and let clinicians use it live since they already know how to use the system?

Answer: Claire agreed to try this approach. She mentioned she could turn it back on and test it, though she wanted to verify with Derek first. She noted that she had already removed the SSO from the environments, so there might be historical context disrupting sign-in ability. She suggested adding Misty to test in the production environment first to ensure it works before rolling it out to all clinicians.

Question 2: When clinicians log in, which site should they use - the temporary test site or the production site?

Answer: Claire confirmed that the test environment had worked perfectly for Derek. However, she indicated she might need engineers to remove certain configurations to resolve the current login issues.

Question 3: When you pulled the users with @Galen email addresses, is it about the same list we have, or did you find additional people?

Answer: Claire offered to show Misty the list she pulled so they could compare. She pulled up the data showing currently six active users who had signed in under their access code. She was able to show Misty which users had been actively using Abridge and when.

Question 4: If clinicians can't get into the current system, can we just make it live in production?

Answer: Claire explained that making it live in production right now would be risky because clinicians would not be able to access their previous notes if they hadn't completed them. She didn't want to lock them out of their current accounts if they had outstanding notes that hadn't been completed yet. She recommended resolving the login issue first before making it live.

Question 5: Do we have Monday off, or are clinicians working on Monday?

Answer: Misty clarified that clinicians are working on Monday (not a holiday). Claire confirmed they would want the issue resolved before then.

Question 6: How did clinicians set up their self-service accounts - through us or on their own?

Answer: Misty indicated she didn't know who was on the list because clinicians had set up accounts on their own. Claire explained that clinicians setting up self-service accounts on their own had created accounts, and when she created the SSO, she didn't provision them there. Their login was still stuck on their self-service accounts. She would need an engineer to wipe that clean and resolve the issue.

Question 7: Can you show me your list of active users so we can compare it to our list?

Answer: Claire pulled up the data showing six users who had ever signed in under their access code. She showed Misty the active users list and was able to display a Gantt chart showing which users had been using Abridge regularly and in which weeks. The six active users were: Tap, Macaulay, Mullins, Height, Norton, and Aaron.

Question 8: Should we remove Khan from the list since she doesn't appear to be using it?

Answer: Claire offered to remove Khan from the list immediately. However, Misty then questioned whether Khan might be logging in under a non-Galen domain. Claire confirmed that would be the only other possibility and that this was a risk with the migration. Misty decided to keep Khan on the list temporarily and verify with her directly before making changes.

Question 9: Can clinicians test the login from their phones to help troubleshoot?

Answer: Claire recommended that clinicians try signing in on their phones again, as that's what they would use for recording (unless they had been doing web recording on their computer). She asked Misty to find out if they could try on their phones and report if the issue was still present.

crm__implementation__keydiscussionpoints.title: Key Discussion Points
crm__implementation__keydiscussionpoints.value:
Based on the transcript, here are the key discussion points addressed during the call:

1. SSO (Single Sign-On) Integration Issues
- The primary issue was that clinicians were unable to log in to Abridge due to SSO configuration problems
- The error message displayed: "Sorry, there was an issue signing you in. Unsupported auth type undefined"
- Claire had removed SSO from both production and staging environments to resolve conflicts
- The problem stemmed from users having self-serve accounts with the same domain name, which conflicted with the new SSO setup

2. User Access Management
- Discussion about which clinicians were actively using Abridge versus those who claimed to be using it
- Verification of the current user list: 6 active users identified (Tapp, Macaulay, Mullins, Height, Norton, Aaron)
- Consideration of removing Khan from the list due to apparent non-usage to avoid unnecessary charges
- Addition of new users: Jolly and Barker identified as new users to be added

3. Migration Strategy and Timing
- Concern about making the system live in production while users had incomplete notes from previous days
- Discussion about the risk of locking users out of their current accounts during migration
- Scheduling considerations around half-day work schedules and the upcoming Monday workday
- Decision to schedule follow-up testing for Monday morning at 7:30

4. User Adoption Challenges
- Some clinicians were hesitant to adopt Abridge
- Misty mentioned one provider who struggles with documenting clinical decision-making but hasn't tried the tool yet
- Discussion about the need for persuasion and one-on-one training for hesitant users
- Recognition that seasoned users were heavily reliant on the tool ("wrecked the world" when it wasn't available)

5. Testing and Troubleshooting Approach
- Need to test login functionality on both desktop/laptop and mobile devices
- Request for screenshots of errors from different devices to diagnose the issue
- Plan for Claire to work with engineers to completely remove historical self-service account data
- Proposal to have Misty test the system once changes were implemented

6. Usage Analytics and Reporting
- Review of usage data showing which users were actively using Abridge and how consistently
- Discussion of a Gantt chart visualization to show user activity patterns over time
- Identification that some users on the list weren't actually using the system despite claims

7. Communication Plans
- Misty planned to send out emails and training invitations to potential new users
- Need to verify with specific users (like Khan) about their actual usage patterns
- Coordination needed with clinicians to attempt test logins

crm__implementation__nextstepsummary__te.title: Next Step Summary
crm__implementation__nextstepsummary__te.value:
Next Steps:

• Claire to work with engineers to resolve SSO login issues preventing clinicians from accessing Abridge (unsupported auth type error)

• Misty to verify with Dr. Khan if she's actively using the platform before finalizing user list

• Follow-up meeting scheduled for Monday, February 16, 2026 at 7:30 AM to retest login access

crm__implementation__risksorblockerstogo.title: Risks or Blockers to Go-Live
crm__implementation__risksorblockerstogo.value:
- SSO authentication issues are preventing user logins due to conflicts between self-service accounts and the new SSO setup, requiring engineering intervention before go-live.
- Incomplete notes migration could lock users out of current accounts and prevent completion of outstanding notes, risking documentation gaps and workflow disruption.
- User list discrepancies (uncertainty about which clinicians are active users) may cause billing issues and unclear adoption metrics, needing verification before full deployment.
